600000060236	2019-04-17	201904	2019-04-17	Repair due to Partially Down	[  "17.04.2019 03:20:53   I. Siemens Healthineers (MEDINVL) Phone 1522/2..Mon_S4K - This 4K magnet (DE) shows a rising Shield TemperatureTrending. https://mrqprod.med.siemens.com/mrquality/work/default.aspx?Nummer=74015&Sel=8 on Wed Apr 17 05:18:16 2019Original message:Node:          MR10836777-74015Message group:Application:   MED_MR_HeMonObject:        EMEASeverity:      MajorText:          Mon_S4K : This 4K magnet (DE) shows a rising Shield Temperature Trending. https://mrqprod.med.siemens.com/mrquality/work/default.aspx?Nummer=74015&Sel=8Time first received: 2019/04/17 05:20:28Time last received: 2019/04/17 07:20:28No. of duplicates since time first received: 0Event Instructions:The 4K magnet shows a rising shield temperature trending.Explanation:The 50K shield temperature is rising due to incorrect operatingpressure of the Helium compressor.Consequence:1. Magnet pressure will increase.2. Magnet will lose Helium.Action:Check the 50K shield temperature progression via MR Quality - Magnet monitoring,If the the temperature shows a continuously rise continue with step 1.1. Check the static pressure of the compressor:ST-7H    ==> 16.0 to 16.5 bar for 50/60 HzF70        ==> 13.5  to 14 bar for 50/60 HzCSW 71 ==> 16.5  to 17 bar for 50/60 Hz2. Refill the compressor with Helium gas according TSG Magnet.3. Search/repair the leakage.Weak points: aeroquip connectors at the cold head and at the compressor.4. Check water flow and water temperature to the compressor.5. Observe the system. A cold head event will indicate a low cold head performance within the next weeks.----------------------------------------------------------------Historic Activities:----------------------------------------------------------------"]	10836777	74015	AMIRA	MAGNETOM AMIRA	Rising shield temperature trend in the 4K magnet, likely due to incorrect Helium compressor operating pressure	No troubleshooting steps were recorded	No corrective action was taken	Compressor	Magnet	201904	DE	Germany	2019-04-17	N	VA12M-SP04	110
